<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98426561272516></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98426561272516><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=98426561272516>RE: Bard Creation Strategy - an argument for agility</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=98426561272516#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=36786><span id= >Lvis</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>9 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Mar 10th 6:06 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have been playing a halfling druid for sometime now and have tried other classes. Finally on a whim I decided to try the bard class. BOY, I wish I would have tried this class sooner. I am having a great time with him. Before I created my bard I thought about his role in groups. I always heard that bards are most effective in large groups. With the new Experience bonus for grouping this class even becomes more so. Since halflings have good Dexderity to start with and I have increased my druid's to 117 I noticed that at about 105&nbsp;&nbsp;more of my spells were continuing to cast even though I was hit in combat.  I chose to focus on Dex and Agi for several reasons. I reasoned that songs like spells might be interupted by attacks. Also, Dex is the "fizzle" facter for bard songs.<br>Lastly, Bards melee. They aren't Tanks in the true since of the word,but,if you melee the less you are hit and the more you hit your opponent the better.  A great Dexterity helps in almost all melee and singing skils. Agility adds to AC, running Speed( I have tested it over and over with my druid using SOW. It may not be much but every little bit helps.) Agility also determines how fast you learn defensive skills(which also adds to AC and to a bards ability to dodge). Thus once again less damage. Bards are able to wear VERY good armor,but are limited by their strength. Boy, that armor weighs a bunch! As stated in the post above Charisma is important when you get to charming and mezzing mobs in higher levels. It will also help you get the best prices when buying or selling. Prices won't very to much on the lower end stuff since it goes up on a % bases. But, higher priced items can really add up. My druid for instance has CHA jewelry he carries around and changes too when buyin and selling. A Lords Tunic for instance will sell to merchant for about 47 PP if he just stays at  his standard 45 CHA, but when he changes out to his +CHA armor he gets 64PP for the same Tunic when he sells. All in all my basic design was this. My bard will melee but I just want to do a steady decent amount of damage that won't attract too much attention from the mob.(songs  do that enough,oy!) Fast, low damage weapons with a Effect that is defensive in nature(Polished Granite Tomohawk, Screaming Mace, Cat-O-Nine Tails,etc.) boosts my defenses and doesn't aggro the mob as much. Second, invest in the best items for AC, DEX, AGI, and CHA. Heck, with a Mask of Deception and a Crude Stein you get a REAL BIG boost to CHA. Third get those magic instruments. Mistmoore Drum would be my first pick. Also keep a hand drum in bank for corpse runs. It can make a big difference on traveling time.  <br>There are alot of +AGI magic items out there. Some Good +CHA jewelry and it seems to me less +Dex magic Items. therefore I used my bonus points this way. Human bard--+10 pts to CHA, +8 pts.DEX, +7 Pts AGI. If I could of I sure would like to have had a few to put into STR. You may want to slide a few from AGI or DEX over to STR if you are a Elf or H-Elf.<br><br>May you never lose your Voice and may your instruments always play true,<br><br>Lvis<br>    <br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
